# SonarQube / ESLint Prevention Patterns

These are the exact patterns that triggered SonarQube issues in this codebase and how to fix them. Follow these rules on every new file and edit to prevent regressions.

---

## React / JSX

### S3735 — Remove `void` operator
Never use `void fn()` to discard a promise. In `useEffect`, call the async function directly.

```tsx
// WRONG
useEffect(() => { void loadData() }, [loadData])

// CORRECT
useEffect(() => { loadData() }, [loadData])
```

### S3358 — No nested ternaries
Never nest one ternary inside another. Extract to `if/else` or a named variable before the JSX return.

```tsx
// WRONG
{loading ? 'Saving…' : editing ? 'Save Changes' : 'Add'}

// CORRECT
const saveLabel = editing ? 'Save Changes' : 'Add'
return <Button>{loading ? 'Saving…' : saveLabel}</Button>

// WRONG — stacked ternary chain
const rows = tab === 'A' ? listA : tab === 'B' ? listB : listC

// CORRECT
let rows: typeof listA
if (tab === 'A') rows = listA
else if (tab === 'B') rows = listB
else rows = listC
```

### S6478 — No component definitions inside parent components
Never define a React component inside another component or inside a `.map()` callback. Hoist it to module level and pass data as props.

```tsx
// WRONG
function Parent() {
  function Child({ value }: { value: string }) { ... }
  return <Legend formatter={(v) => <Child value={v} />} />
}

// CORRECT
function Child({ value }: Readonly<{ value: string }>) { ... }
function renderChild(value: string) { return <Child value={value} /> }
function Parent() {
  return <Legend formatter={renderChild} />
}
```

### S7735 — No negated conditions
Always write the positive condition first and put the main path in the truthy branch.

```tsx
// WRONG
{!s ? <EmptyState /> : <Content data={s} />}

// CORRECT
{s ? <Content data={s} /> : <EmptyState />}

// WRONG — negated comparison
return idx !== -1 ? arr[idx + 1] : undefined

// CORRECT
return idx === -1 ? undefined : arr[idx + 1]

// WRONG — negated null check
const hours = row.hours != null ? String(row.hours) : ''

// CORRECT
const hours = row.hours == null ? '' : String(row.hours)

// WRONG — pluralization with negation
`${count} result${count !== 1 ? 's' : ''}`

// CORRECT
`${count} result${count === 1 ? '' : 's'}`
```

### S6759 — Mark component props as read-only
Always wrap inline prop types with `Readonly<>`. For named interfaces, add `readonly` to each field.

```tsx
// WRONG
function Card({ title, count }: { title: string; count: number }) {}

// CORRECT
function Card({ title, count }: Readonly<{ title: string; count: number }>) {}

// WRONG — named interface
interface Props { title: string; count: number }

// CORRECT
interface Props { readonly title: string; readonly count: number }
// or use Readonly<Props> at the function call site
function Card({ title, count }: Readonly<Props>) {}
```

### next/link — Use `<Link>` for internal navigation
Never use `<a href="/internal-path">` inside Next.js components. Import and use `Link` from `next/link`.

```tsx
// WRONG
<a href="/settings/org-levels">Settings</a>

// CORRECT
import Link from 'next/link'
<Link href="/settings/org-levels">Settings</Link>
```

### Unescaped entities in JSX
Use HTML entities or JavaScript strings for quotes and special characters in JSX text.

```tsx
// WRONG
<p>Don't use raw apostrophes</p>

// CORRECT
<p>Don&apos;t use raw apostrophes</p>
// or
<p>{"Don't use raw apostrophes"}</p>
```

### React `key` must be a primitive
Never use an object as a `key` prop. Use a string or number property of the object.

```tsx
// WRONG — obj is Record<string, unknown>
{items.map(item => <Tag key={item} />)}

// CORRECT
{items.map(item => <Tag key={item.id} />)}
```

