## Performance / Correctness

### S7776 — Use `Set` for membership checks
Role/permission arrays used only for `.includes()` checks must be `Set` so lookups are O(1).

```ts
// WRONG
const ADMIN_ROLES = ['SUPER_ADMIN', 'TENANT_ADMIN', 'HR_ADMIN']
if (!ADMIN_ROLES.includes(profile.role)) { ... }

// CORRECT
const ADMIN_ROLES = new Set(['SUPER_ADMIN', 'TENANT_ADMIN', 'HR_ADMIN'])
if (!ADMIN_ROLES.has(profile.role)) { ... }
```

### S6582 — Prefer optional chaining
Replace `x && x.y` with `x?.y`.

```ts
// WRONG
const rate = ot && ot.fixedRateAmount > 0 ? ot.fixedRateAmount : null

// CORRECT
const rate = (ot?.fixedRateAmount && ot.fixedRateAmount > 0) ? ot.fixedRateAmount : null
```

### S7781 — Prefer `replaceAll` for literal patterns
When the search pattern is a literal string (not a regex), use `replaceAll` instead of `.replace(/pat/g, ...)`.

```ts
// WRONG
text.replace(/_/g, ' ')
text.replace(/\n/g, '<br />')

// CORRECT
text.replaceAll('_', ' ')
text.replaceAll('\n', '<br />')
```

### S4624 — No nested template literals
Extract the inner expression to a named variable before using it in the outer template.

```ts
// WRONG
`${country}${city ? `, ${city}` : ''}`

// CORRECT
const citySuffix = city ? `, ${city}` : ''
`${country}${citySuffix}`
// or use an if/else block in JSX
```

### S8786 — Avoid ReDoS-prone regexes
Never nest a quantified group inside another quantifier: `(?:...)+` where `...` itself contains `+` or `*`.

```ts
// WRONG — nested quantifier causes backtracking
/[a-zA-Z0-9-]+(?:\.[a-zA-Z0-9-]+)+/

// CORRECT — flattened, no nesting
/[a-zA-Z0-9.-]+\.[a-zA-Z]{2,}/
```

### S7780 — Use `String.raw` for Windows paths in scripts
Node.js scripts that contain Windows backslash paths should use `String.raw` to avoid double-escaping. (Note: do NOT use `String.raw` in Next.js `config.matcher` — Turbopack cannot statically analyze it.)

```js
// WRONG (in a plain Node.js script)
const bin = 'node_modules\\.bin\\next.cmd'

// CORRECT
const bin = String.raw`node_modules\.bin\next.cmd`
```

### S7772 — Use the `node:` protocol for built-in modules
Always import Node.js built-ins with the `node:` prefix.

```js
// WRONG
const { spawn } = require('child_process')

// CORRECT
const { spawn } = require('node:child_process')
```

### S3863 — Merge duplicate imports
Never import from the same module twice. Combine into a single import statement.

```ts
// WRONG
import { notFound } from 'next/navigation'
import { redirect } from 'next/navigation'

// CORRECT
import { notFound, redirect } from 'next/navigation'
```

### S6551 — Explicit string conversion for template literals
`Record<string, unknown>` values interpolated into template literals will produce `[object Object]`. Cast with `String()`.

```ts
// detail is Record<string, unknown>
// WRONG
`Entity: ${detail.name}`

// CORRECT
`Entity: ${String(detail.name)}`
```

